{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> θῡμός</b>, ὁ, <br /> <b>soul, spirit</b>, as <b>the principle of life, feeling and thought</b>, especially <b>of strong feeling and passion</b> (rightly derived from θύω (B) by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 419e ἀπὸ τῆς θύσεως καὶ ζέσεως τῆς ψυχῆς): \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> in physical sense, <b>breath, life</b>, θ. ἀπηύρα, ἀφελέσθαι, ἐξαίνυσθαι, ὀλέσαι, frequently in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.17, 5.852, 155, 1.205: with double _accusative_, ἄμφω θ. ἀπηύρα 6.17; ἐπεί κε.. ῥεθέων ἐκ θ. ἕληται 22.68; λίπε δ᾽ ὀστέα θ. 12.386 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἀπὸ δ᾽ ἔπτατο θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.163; ὀλίγος δ᾽ ἔτι θ. ἐνῆεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.593; μόγις δ᾽ ἐσαγείρετο θυμόν 21.417; ἄψορρόν οἱ θ. ἐνὶ στήθεσσιν ἀγέρθη 4.152; θυμοῦ καὶ ψυχῆς κεκαδών 11.334 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of animals, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3.294, 12.150 \">Refs</a>], etc.: less frequently in Trag., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1388, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 620 (troch.). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>spirit, strength</b>, τείρετο δ᾽ ἀνδρῶν θ. ὑπ᾽ εἰρεσίης [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.78; ἐν δέ τε θ. τείρεθ᾽ ὁμοῦ καμάτῳ τε καὶ ἱδρῷ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.744. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.3</b></Level3> πάτασσε δὲ θ. ἑκάστου each man's <b>heart</b> beat high, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.370, compare 7.216. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>soul</b>, as shown by the feelings and passions; and so, <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> <b>desire</b> or <b>inclination</b>, especially desire for meat and drink, <b>appetite</b>, πιέειν ὅτε θ. ἀνώγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.263; πλησάμενος.. θυμὸν ἐδητύος ἠδὲ ποτῆτος 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.603: generally, τά με θ. ἐνὶ στήθεσσι κελεύει 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.68 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; βαλέειν δέ ἑ ἵετο θ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\". 8.301; αἲ γάρ με μένος καὶ θ. ἀνείη 22.346 \">Refs</a>]; θ. ἐποτρύνῃ [τινά] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.139 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; θ. ἐπέσσυταί τινι, ἐφορμᾶται, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.173, 13.73 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἤθελε θυμῷ he wished <b>in his heart</b> or <b>with all his heart</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.255, 21.65; ἵετο θυμῷ 2.589 \">Refs</a>]; so later θυμῷ βουλόμενοι wishing <b>with all their heart</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.49; [ὄσσα ϝ] οι θ. κε θέλῃ γένεσθαι 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 1.3; θυμὸς ὥρμα 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 3.25, compare 38; θυμὸς ἡδονὴν φέρει 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 286; ὧν ἐρᾷ θυμός 3rd c.BC: Herodas Mimographus 7.61; τῶν σφι θ. ἦν μάλιστα 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.1; ἄλλως σφι θ. ἐγένετο θεήσασθαι τὸν πόλεμον [prev. author] 8.116, etc.: with Verb omitted, σὲ γάρ μοι θῦμος ὔμνην 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus 5 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; ἄρχ᾽ αὐτὸς ὥς σοι θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1319 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὅπου ὑμῖν θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 3.1.37; βῆξαι θυμός ἐγγίνεται 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “προγνωστικόν” 8. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>mind, temper, will</b>, θ. πρόφρων, ἵλαος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.39, 9.639; θ. ὑπερφίαλος καὶ ἀπηνής, νηλέα θ. ἔχοντας, σιδήρεος θ., 15.94, 19.229, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.191 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἕνα θ. ἔχειν to be of one <b>mind</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.710, etc.; οὐδὲ λύκοι τε καὶ ἄρνες ὁμόφρονα θ. ἔχουσιν 22.263; ἕτερος δέ με θ. ἔρυκε 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.302 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐμὸν θ. ἔπειθεν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 33; θωπείας κολακικάς, αἳ.. τοὺς θ. ποιοῦσιν κηρίνους 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 633d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>spirit, courage</b>, μένος καὶ θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.174; θ. ἐνὶ στήθεσσι λαβεῖν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.461 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πᾶσιν δὲ παραὶ ποσὶ κάππεσε θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.280 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ψῦχρος ἔγεντο θ., of doves, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 16; θ. ἔχειν ἀγαθόν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.120; θ. οὐκ ἀπώλεσεν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 26; ὁ θυμὸς εὐθὺς ἦν Ἀμυνίας 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 570 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; ἴωμεν ῥώμῃ καὶ θυμῷ ἐπί.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.2.21; φρονήματός τε καὶ θυμοῦ ἐμπίπλασθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 411c: so in Philos., opposed to λόγος, ἐπιθυμία, [prev. work] 440b, +others,compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1328a7, 1327b24, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Mus.” p.26K., etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; personified, <b>Passion, Emotion</b>, opposed to Λογισμός, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Cleanthes Stoicus 1.129. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>the seat of anger</b>, χωόμενον κατὰ θυμόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.429; νεμεσιζέσθω ἐνὶ θυμῷ 17.254; θυμὸν ἐχώσατο 16.616, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: hence, <b>anger, wrath</b>, δάμασον θυμόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.496 \">Refs</a>]; εἴξας ᾧ θυμῷ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 598; θυμὸς μέγας ἐστὶ.. βασιλήων 2.196; θ. ὀξύς 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1193; θ. κρείσσων τῶν ἐμῶν βουλευμάτων 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 1079, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; θυμῷ <i>falsa lectio</i> for{θυμοῦ} in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 718; οἱ τῷ θ. πραχθέντες φόνοι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 867b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to λογισμός, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.11, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπανάγειν τὸν θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.160; ἐκτείνειν 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 3.31; καταθέσθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 567; δακεῖν [prev. author] “Nu.” 1369; θυμῷ χρᾶσθαι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.137, +others; ὀργῆς καὶ θυμοῦ μεστοί 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 12.81 (so τὴν ὀργὴν καὶ τὸν θ., i.e. the outward manifestation of ὀ., 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Ir.” p.90W.) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of horses, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 9.2: _plural_ (not earlier than 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus, _falsa lectio_ in 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 718 (Lyric poetry))\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <b>fits of anger, passions</b>, περὶ φόβων τε καὶ θυμῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Philebus” 40e; οἵ τε θ. καὶ αἱ κολάσεις [prev. author] “Prt.” 323e, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1390a11. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.5</b></Level3> <b>the heart</b>, as the seat of the emotions, especially joy or grief, χαῖρε, γήθησε δὲ θυμῷ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.156, 7.189; θ. ἐνὶ στήθεσσι γεγήθει 13.494; μιν ἄχος κραδίην καὶ θ. ἵκανεν 2.171; ἄχνυτο θ. 14.39, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; δόκησε δ᾽ ἄρα σφίσι θ. ὣς ἔμεν ὡς εἰ.. they felt as glad at <b>heart</b> as if.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.415 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; μηδ᾽ ὀνίαισι δάμνα.. θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 1.4 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; of fear, δέος ἔμπεσε θυμῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.625, compare 8.138 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of love, τὴν ἐκ θυμοῦ φίλεον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.343; ἐκ θυμοῦ στέργοισα 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 17.130 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; ἐμῷ κεχαρισμένε θυμῷ my <b>heart's</b> beloved, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.243 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; reversely, ἀπὸ θ. μᾶλλον ἐμοὶ ἔσεαι wilt be alien from my <b>heart</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.562 \">Refs</a>]; ἐκ θ. πεσέειν, i.e. to lose thy favour,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.595; ἔρωτι θυμὸν ἐκπλαγεῖσα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 8; ἐκ θ. κλαῦσαι 4th-3rd c.BC: Philetas 11. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.6</b></Level3> <b>mind, soul, as the seat of thought</b>, ταῦθ᾽ ὥρμαινε κατὰ φρένα καὶ κατὰ θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.193, etc.; ᾔδεε γὰρ κατὰ θ. 2.409, compare 4.163, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; φράζετο θυμῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 16.646; ἐν θ. ἐβάλοντο ἔπος 15.566; τοὺς λόγους θυμῷ βάλε 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 706; εἰς θ. βαλεῖν τι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 975 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐκ ἐς θ. φέρω I bring him not into my <b>mind</b> or <b>thoughts</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “El.” 1347. \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G2372","accentedUnicode":"θυμός","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G2371","matchingForm":"θυμομαχέω","stepTransliteration":"thumomacheō","gloss":"to quarrel","_zh_tw_Gloss":"惱怒","_es_Gloss":"discutir","_zh_Gloss":"恼怒"},{"strongNumber":"G2373","matchingForm":"θυμόω","stepTransliteration":"thumoō","gloss":"to anger","_zh_tw_Gloss":"發怒","_es_Gloss":"enojar","_zh_Gloss":"发怒"},{"strongNumber":"G3116","matchingForm":"μακροθυμώς","stepTransliteration":"makrothumōs","gloss":"patiently","_zh_tw_Gloss":"耐心","_es_Gloss":"pacientemente","_zh_Gloss":"耐心"}],"shortDef":"wrath, fury, anger, rage, a state of intense displeasure based in some real or perceived wrong. \"The anger of God\" is due to moral offense and has a focus on righteous punishment","mediumDef":"wrath, fury, anger, rage, a state of intense displeasure based in some real or perceived wrong. \"The anger of God\" is due to moral offense and has a focus on righteous punishment <br /><i>primarily</i> <b>the soul, mind;</b> hence, <b>a strong passion</b> or <b>emotion of the mind; anger, wrath, rage</b> <ref='Luk.4.28'>Lk. 4:28</ref>; <ref='Act.19.28'>Acts 19:28;</ref> <i>plural</i> <b>swellings of anger,</b> <ref='2Co.12.20'>2Cor. 12:20;</ref> <ref='Gal.5.20'>Gal. 5:20</ref>","stepGloss":"wrath","stepTransliteration":"thumos","count":18,"_es_Definition":"enojo, ira, furia ; sentimiento intenso","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 激情, 強烈的渴望 #啟 14:8,16:19,18:3,19:15|<br>2) 忿怒, 憎惡","_zh_Definition":"1) 激情, 强烈的渴望 #启 14:8,16:19,18:3,19:15|<br>2) 忿怒, 憎恶","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"sự giận dữ mãnh liệt; sự căm phẫn, sự phẫn nộ; sự tức giận tột bực.","_zh_tw_Gloss":"大怒","_es_Gloss":"ira","_zh_Gloss":"大怒"}]}